{"properties":{"genre":"Article","timestamp":"2014-02-11T15:57:33Z","author":["Robbins, Travis R.","Walker, Lorelei E.","Gorospe, Kelvin D.","Karl, Stephen A.","McCoy, Earl D.","Mushinsky, Henry R.","Schrey, Aaron W."],"title":"Data from: Rise and fall of a hybrid zone: implications for the roles of aggression, mate choice, and secondary succession","host":"Robbins TR, Walker LE, Gorospe KD, Karl SA, Schrey AW, McCoy ED, Mushinsky HR (2013) Rise and fall of a hybrid zone: implications for the roles of aggression, mate choice, and secondary succession. Journal of Heredity 105(2): 226-236.","keywords":["introgression","Conservation genetics and biodiversity","territoriality","Transgressive segregation","phylogeographic discordance","Population structure and phylogeography","metapopulation dynamics"],"description":"Hybridization can be an important evolutionary force by generating new species and influencing evolution of parental species in multiple ways, including introgression and the consequences of hybrid vigor. Determining the ecological processes underlying evolution in hybrid zones is difficult however because it requires examining changes in both genotypic frequencies over time and corresponding ecological information, data that are rarely collected together. Here, we describe genetic and ecological aspects of a hybrid zone between the Eastern Fence Lizard, Sceloporus undulatus, and the Florida Scrub Lizard, Sceloporus woodi, occurring over at least 23 generations. The hybrid zone, discovered greater than 35 years ago using morphological characters, originally consisted of nearly even proportions of parental species and hybrids. Now, using genetic markers (species-diagnostic mtDNA sites and 6 nDNA microsatellite loci across a total of n = 117 individuals), we confirm not only that hybridization occurred but also that subsequent backcrossing has resulted in highly introgressed hybrids, with many hybrids containing mitochondrial DNA from one species on a nuclear 